homas Aquinas, Averroes, Maimonides and Duns Scotus – into conversation with those not usually considered canonical – Nicholas of Cusa, Marsilius of Padua, Gersonides and Moses Almosnino. Medieval and Renaissance thought is approached with contemporary continental philosophy in view, highlighting the continued richness and relevance of the work from this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 0aPhilosophy, Renaissance. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAleksander, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasarella, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastañeda, Felipe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaygill, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlstrom, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobbs-Weinstein, Idit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalque, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankey, Wayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Josh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan, Mark D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufman, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabinski, Maggie Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee Jr., Richard A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMacKendrick, Karmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahoney, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarmo, Costantino, econtributor.4ctb